According to Section 54 of the Labour Act 2004, a pregnant employee is entitled to:

1. Leave work before confinement if medically certified (Section 54(1)(a));
2. Not be permitted to work during the six weeks following her confinement (Section 54(1)(b));
3. Be paid at least 50% of her wages for six months prior to her absence, if she is absent from her work in pursuance of paragraph (a) or (b) of this subsection (Section 54(1)(c));
4. Be allowed half an hour twice a day during her working hours for nursing her child (Section 54(1)(d));

Additionally, Section 54(4) states that an employer shall not give notice of dismissal during her absence or notice of dismissal expiring during her absence, if she is absent from her work in pursuance of subsection (1)(a) or (b) of this section.

Therefore, a pregnant employee in Nigeria is entitled to six weeks of paid maternity leave, with at least 50% of her wages paid for six months prior to her absence, and is also entitled to nursing breaks.

According to Section 25 of the Lagos Tenancy Law 2011, a landlord can recover possession of his premises from a tenant on the following grounds:

(a) arrears of rent;
(b) breach of any covenant or agreement;
(c) where the premises is required by the landlord for personal use; or

Additionally, Section 2 of the same section overrides agreements for certain severe violations.

However, Section 39 of the same law states that the court may issue a warrant for possession, even if the tenant has an undetermined or unsatisfied counterclaim.

According to Section 187 of the Nigeria Tax Act 2025, the following taxable supplies are charged to VAT at the rate of 0%:

(a) basic food items;
(b) all medical and pharmaceutical products including medicinal herbal products;
(c) educational books and materials;
(d) fertilisers;
(e) locally produced agricultural chemicals;
(f) locally produced veterinary medicine;
(g) locally produced animal feeds;
(h) live cattle, goats, sheep and poultry;
(i) agricultural seeds and seedlings;
(j) electricity generated by generation companies (GENCOs) and supplied to National Grid or Nigeria Bulk Electricity Trading Company (NBET);
(k) electricity transmitted by Transmission Company of Nigeria (TCN) to Electricity Distribution Companies (DISCOs);
(l) medical services;
(m) tuition relating to nursery, primary, secondary or tertiary education;
(n) exported goods excluding oil and gas;
(o) exported services;
(p) exported incorporeal property;
(q) medical equipment;
(r) electric vehicles; and
(s) parts, semi-knock-down units for the assembly of Electric Vehicles.

